  "why": "The paper does not evaluate whether fault-inducing prompts discovered on one model transfer to other, independently trained target models, nor does it include explicit design choices to discover transferable failures across models. The authors evaluate SneakyPrompt on multiple safety filters and on two target systems (Stable Diffusion and DALL·E 2) by running the attack separately on each, and they study “re-use” of prompts (i.e., reuse on the same model across seeds or repeated attempts). However, they do not report experiments where adversarial prompts found against a surrogate or one model are applied to a different unseen target model to measure cross-model transferability, and they do not incorporate cross-model guidance into the fuzzer design.",
  "evidence": "Page 3, Section 3.2 Threat Model: \"One-time attack: The adversary searches adversarial prompts for one-time use... Re-use attack: The adversary obtains adversarial prompts generated by other adversaries or by themselves in previous one-time attacks, and then re-uses the provided adversarial prompts for NSFW images.\" (defines reuse on the same model/setting).\n\nPage 7, Section 5 Experimental Setup: \"Our target text-to-image models include (i) Stable Diffusion with the open source model on Hugging Face [42] and (ii) DALL·E 2 with the official online API provided by OpenAI [43].\" (shows they target each model separately).\n\nPage 9, Table 2 and surrounding text (Section 6.1 RQ1): results report bypass rates separately for Stable Diffusion (various safety filters) and for DALL·E 2; the paper reports one-time and re-use performance but does not present experiments where prompts found on one model are applied to a different model.\n\nPage 12, Section 6.3 Shadow Text Encoder: \"Table 8 shows the impact of different shadow text encoders Eˆ, particularly when Eˆ = E and Eˆ ̸= E... There is no significant difference in bypass rates and the number of online queries.\" (discusses shadow encoder matching, not cross-model transfer).\n\nAppendix B Meta-Review (Page 16): \"The paper lacks evidence showcasing the broader applicability of the proposed attack on closed-box safety filters, as the only closed-box filter evaluated is DALL·E 2.\" (acknowledges limited cross-system evaluation)."
